[src:podman/docker-software] The core software that runs and manages these containers is called **Docker Engine**.
[src:podman/docker-software] Docker was first released in 2013 and continues to be developed by Docker, Inc.
[src:podman/docker-software] The platform includes both free and paid tiers.
[src:podman/docker-software] Solomon Hykes started the Docker project in France as an internal project within dotCloud, a platform-as-a-service company.
[src:podman/docker-software] dotCloud Inc. was founded by Kamel Founadi, Hykes, and Sebastien Pahl during the Y Combinator Summer 2010 startup incubator group and launched in 2011, and renamed to Docker Inc in 2013.
[src:podman/docker-software] Docker debuted to the public in Santa Clara at PyCon in 2013.
[src:podman/docker-software] It was released as open-source in March 2013.
[src:podman/docker-software] At the time, it used LXC as its default execution environment.
[src:podman/docker-software] One year later, with the release of version 0.9, Docker replaced LXC with its own component, *libcontainer*, which was written in the Go programming language.
[src:podman/docker-software] In 2017, Docker created the Moby project for open research and development.
[src:podman/docker-software] In March 2026, the Communications of the ACM featured Docker as the cover article in a retrospective article of the past decade.
[src:podman/docker-software] Containers are isolated from one another and bundle their own software, libraries and configuration files; they can communicate with each other through well-defined channels.
[src:podman/docker-software] Because all of the containers share the services of a single operating system kernel, they use fewer resources than virtual machines.
[src:podman/docker-software] Docker can package an application and its dependencies in a virtual container that can, in principle, run on any Linux, Windows, or macOS computer.
[src:podman/docker-software] This enables the application to run in a variety of locations, such as on-premises, in public *(see decentralized computing, distributed computing, and cloud computing)* or private cloud.
[src:podman/docker-software] Docker on macOS uses a Linux virtual machine to run the containers.
[src:podman/docker-software] Because Docker containers are lightweight, a single server or virtual machine can run several containers simultaneously.
[src:podman/docker-software] A 2018 analysis found that a typical Docker use case involves running eight containers per host, and that a quarter of analyzed organizations run 18 or more per host.
[src:podman/docker-software] It can also be installed on a single board computer like the Raspberry Pi.
[src:podman/docker-software] The Linux kernel's support for namespaces mostly isolates an application's view of the operating environment, including process trees, network, user IDs and mounted file systems, while the kernel's cgroups provide resource limiting for memory and CPU.
[src:podman/docker-software] Since version 0.9, Docker includes its own component (called libcontainer) to use virtualization facilities provided directly by the Linux kernel, in addition to using abstracted virtualization interfaces via libvirt, LXC and systemd-nspawn.
[src:podman/docker-software] Docker implements a high-level API to provide lightweight containers that run processes in isolation.
[src:podman/docker-software] , is a persistent process that manages Docker containers and handles container objects.
[src:podman/docker-software] The daemon listens for requests that are sent via the Docker Engine API.
[src:podman/docker-software] (CLI) that allows users to interact with Docker daemons.
[src:podman/docker-software] Docker objects are various entities used to assemble an application in Docker.
[src:podman/docker-software] The main classes of Docker objects are images, containers, and services.
[src:podman/docker-software] A Docker registry is a repository for Docker images.
[src:podman/docker-software] Docker clients connect to registries to download ("pull") images for use or upload ("push") images that they have built.
[src:podman/docker-software] Docker Hub is the default registry where Docker looks for images.
[src:podman/docker-software] Docker registries also allow the creation of notifications based on events.
[src:podman/docker-software] A Dockerfile is a text file that commonly specifies several aspects of a Docker container: the Linux distribution, installation commands for the programming language runtime environment and application source code.
[src:podman/introduction] Containers simplify the production, distribution, discoverability, and usage of applications with all of their dependencies and default configuration files.
[src:podman/introduction] Users test drive or deploy a new application with one or two commands instead of following pages of installation instructions.
[src:podman/introduction] The previous command returned a list of publicly available container images on DockerHub.
[src:podman/introduction] These container images are easy to consume, but of differing levels of quality and maintenance.
[src:podman/introduction] Let’s use the first one listed because it seems to be well maintained.
[src:podman/introduction] There’s an old saying that “nobody runs an operating system just to run an operating system” and the same is true with containers.
[src:podman/introduction] It’s the workload running on top of an operating system or in a container that’s interesting and valuable.
[src:podman/introduction] Sometimes we can find a publicly available container image for the exact workload we’re looking for and it will already be packaged exactly how we want.
[src:podman/introduction] But, more often than not, there’s something that we want to add, remove, or customize.
[src:podman/introduction] It can be as simple as a configuration setting for security or performance, or as complex as adding a complex workload.
[src:podman/introduction] Either way, containers make it fairly easy to make the changes we need.
[src:podman/introduction] Container Images aren’t actually images.
[src:podman/introduction] They are repositories often made up of multiple layers.
[src:podman/introduction] These layers can easily be added, saved, and shared with others by using a Containerfile (Dockerfile).
[src:podman/introduction] This single file often contains all the instructions needed to build a new container image and can easily be shared with others publicly using tools like GitHub.
[src:podman/introduction] Building new images is great, but sharing our work with others lets them review our work, critique how we built them, and offer improved versions.
[src:podman/introduction] Our newly built *hello* image can be published at quay.io or docker.io to share it with the world.
[src:podman/introduction] Everything needed to run the *hello* application is provided in the container image.
[src:podman/introduction] Others can easily pull it down and use it, or make improvements to it.
[src:podman/introduction] Standardizing on container images and Container Registries enable a new level of collaboration through simple consumption.
[src:podman/introduction] This simple consumption model is possible because every major Container Engine and Registry Server uses the Open Containers Initiative (OCI) format.
[src:podman/introduction] This allows users to find, run, build, share and deploy containers anywhere they want.
[src:podman/introduction] Podman and other Container Engines like CRI-O, Docker, or containerd can create and consume container images from docker.io, quay.io, an on premise registry or even one provided by a cloud provider.
[src:podman/introduction] The OCI image format facilitates this ecosystem through a single standard.
[src:podman/introduction] For example, if we wanted to share our newly built *hello* container image on quay.io it’s easy.
[src:podman/introduction] Notice that we pushed one layer to our registry and now it’s available for others to share.
[src:podman/introduction] To summarize, Podman makes it easy to find, run, build and share containers.
[src:podman/introduction] For more instructions on use cases, take a look at our Tutorials page.
[src:podman/latest] Podman is a daemonless, open source, Linux native tool designed to make it easy to find, run, build, share and deploy applications using Open Containers Initiative (OCI) Containers and Container Images.
[src:podman/latest] Podman provides a command line interface (CLI) familiar to anyone who has used the Docker Container Engine.
[src:podman/latest] Most users can simply alias Docker to Podman (*alias docker=podman*) without any problems.
[src:podman/latest] Similar to other common Container Engines (Docker, CRI-O, containerd), Podman relies on an OCI compliant Container Runtime (runc, crun, runv, etc) to interface with the operating system and create the running containers.
[src:podman/latest] This makes the running containers created by Podman nearly indistinguishable from those created by any other common container engine.
[src:podman/latest] Containers under the control of Podman can either be run by root or by a non-privileged user.
[src:podman/latest] Podman manages the entire container ecosystem which includes pods, containers, container images, and container volumes using the libpod library.
[src:podman/latest] Podman specializes in all of the commands and functions that help you to maintain and modify OCI container images, such as pulling and tagging.
[src:podman/latest] It allows you to create, run, and maintain those containers and container images in a production environment.
[src:podman/latest] There is a RESTFul API to manage containers.
[src:podman/latest] We also have a remote Podman client that can interact with the RESTFul service.
[src:podman/latest] We currently support clients on Linux, Mac, and Windows.
[src:podman/latest] The RESTFul service is only supported on Linux.
[src:podman/latest] If you are completely new to containers, we recommend that you check out the Introduction.
[src:podman/latest] For power users or those coming from Docker, check out our Tutorials.
[src:podman/latest] For advanced users and contributors, you can get very detailed information about the Podman CLI by looking at our Commands page.
[src:podman/latest] Finally, for Developers looking at how to interact with the Podman API, please see our API documentation Reference.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:podman/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
[src:podman/page] Podman is a utility provided as part of the libpod library.
[src:podman/page] It can be used to create and maintain containers.
[src:podman/page] The following tutorial will teach you how to set up Podman and perform some basic commands.
[src:podman/page] The documentation for Podman is located here.
[src:podman/page] For installing or building Podman, please see the installation instructions.
[src:podman/page] The code samples are intended to be run as a non-root user, and use `sudo` where root escalation is required.
[src:podman/page] Please also reference the Podman Troubleshooting Guide to find known issues and tips on how to solve common configuration mistakes.
[src:podman/page] Podman can search for images on remote registries with some simple keywords.
[src:podman/page] Downloading (Pulling) an image is easy, too.
[src:podman/page] After pulling some images, you can list all images, present on your machine.
[src:podman/page] This sample container will run a very basic httpd server that serves only its index page.
[src:podman/page] The `podman ps` command is used to list created and running containers.
[src:podman/page] As you are able to see, the container does not have an IP Address assigned.
[src:podman/page] The container is reachable via it's published port on your local machine.
[src:podman/page] From another machine, you need to use the IP Address of the host, running the container.
[src:podman/page] You can "inspect" a running container for metadata and details about itself.
[src:podman/page] `podman inspect` will provide lots of useful information like environment variables, network settings or allocated resources.
[src:podman/page] Since, the container is running in **rootless** mode, no IP Address is assigned to the container.
[src:podman/page] You can observe the httpd pid in the container with `podman top`.
[src:podman/page] You can check the status of one or more containers using the `podman ps` command.
[src:podman/page] In this case, you should use the `-a` argument to list all containers.
[src:podman/page] You can verify the deletion of the container by running `podman ps -a`.
[src:podman/page] For a more detailed guide about Networking and DNS in containers, please see the network guide.
[src:podman/page] Checkpointing a container stops the container while writing the state of all processes in the container to disk.
[src:podman/page] With this, a container can later be migrated and restored, running at exactly the same point in time as the checkpoint.
[src:podman/page] For more details, see the checkpoint instructions.
[src:podman/page] For more information on how to setup and run the integration tests in your environment, checkout the Integration Tests README.md.
[src:podman/page] The documentation for the Podman Python SDK is located here.
[src:podman/page] For more information on Podman and its subcommands, checkout the asciiart demos on the README.md page.
[src:podman/podman] The first public release of Podman (v0.2) was released in 2018, version 1.0.0 of Podman was released on January 16th, 2019.
[src:podman/podman] Version 1.0 of Podman Desktop was released on May 23, 2023.
[src:podman/podman] In KubeCon 2024, Red Hat announced that it will contribute Podman and Podman Desktop to the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), by that point, Podman Desktop had already been downloaded 1.5 million times, the projects were accepted into the CNCF on January 21, 2025.
[src:podman/podman] In the 2025 Stack Overflow survey, among 20,070 survey respondents identifying as professionals, 10.9% said that they had used Podman in the past year, compared to 73.8% and 30.1% for Docker and Kubernetes respectively.
[src:podman/podman] Podman is a "daemonless" tool, as opposed to other containerization systems like Docker, which uses a background service called *dockerd* to manage its containers, Podman relies on systemd for managing its container life cycles.
[src:podman/podman] Podman lets containers run without root privileges (rootless), meaning they can be created, run, and managed by regular users without administrator rights by using Linux namespaces.
